Complete Filter Chain — All Filters Explained:
Filter 1: DisableEncodeUrlFilter
    /*
     PROBLEM it solves:
     By default, Java appends session ID to URLs:
     /profile;jsessionid=ABC123XYZ   ← security risk! session exposed in URL/logs
     THIS FILTER: Disables that behavior completely
    */
    // What it does internally:
    public class DisableEncodeUrlFilter extends OncePerRequestFilter {
        @Override
        protected void doFilterInternal(HttpServletRequest request, ...) {
            // Wraps response so encodeURL() does nothing
            // Result: /profile  (clean, no session ID leak)
            filterChain.doFilter(new DisableEncodeUrlResponseWrapper(response), response);
        }
    }
    In JWT — essential. JWT is stateless, session IDs in URLs are meaningless and dangerous.

Filter 2: WebAsyncManagerIntegrationFilter
    /*
     PROBLEM it solves:
     Async requests (@Async, DeferredResult, Callable) run on DIFFERENT threads.
     SecurityContext (who is logged in) is stored per-thread.
     Without this filter → async thread has NO idea who the user is!
    */
    @GetMapping("/report")
    public Callable<Report> generateReport() {
        return () -> {
            // This runs on a NEW thread
            // WITHOUT this filter → SecurityContextHolder.getContext() = EMPTY!
            // WITH this filter    → SecurityContextHolder.getContext() = current user ✅
            Authentication auth = SecurityContextHolder.getContext().getAuthentication();
            return reportService.generate(auth.getName());
        };
    }
    In JWT — critical for async endpoints. Propagates JWT-authenticated user to worker threads.

Filter 3: SecurityContextHolderFilter
    /*
     THE MOST FUNDAMENTAL FILTER.
     SecurityContext = a holder that stores WHO is currently logged in.
     This filter LOADS the context at start of request and CLEARS it at end.
     Flow:
     Request Start  → load SecurityContext → put in SecurityContextHolder
     Request End    → clear SecurityContextHolder (prevent memory/security leak)
    */
    // Think of it like:
    public class SecurityContextHolderFilter extends OncePerRequestFilter {
        @Override
        protected void doFilterInternal(HttpServletRequest request, ...) {
            // 1. Load context (from session OR token depending on config)
            SecurityContext context = securityContextRepository.loadContext(request);
            SecurityContextHolder.setContext(context);
            try {
                filterChain.doFilter(request, response);  // process request
            } finally {
                // 2. ALWAYS clear after request — prevent thread reuse leaks
                SecurityContextHolder.clearContext();
            }
        }
    }
      // JWT Usage:
      // Since JWT is STATELESS → context is NOT loaded from session
      // Instead our JwtAuthFilter manually sets the context:
      SecurityContextHolder.getContext().setAuthentication(authToken); // ← we do this

Filter 4: HeaderWriterFilter
    /*
     Automatically adds SECURITY HEADERS to every response.
     Protects against common web attacks.
    */
    // Headers it adds:
    X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
    // → Prevents browser from guessing content type (MIME sniffing attack)
    X-Frame-Options: DENY
    // → Prevents your page from being embedded in <iframe> (Clickjacking attack)
    X-XSS-Protection: 0
    // → Modern browsers have built-in XSS protection, this disables old filter
    Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000
    // → Forces HTTPS for 1 year (HSTS)
    Cache-Control: no-cache, no-store, max-age=0
    // → Prevents sensitive pages being cached in browser
    // Example response headers your API sends automatically:
    HTTP/1.1 200 OK
    X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff      ✅ auto-added
    X-Frame-Options: DENY                ✅ auto-added
    Cache-Control: no-cache, no-store    ✅ auto-added
    In JWT/OAuth2 — runs always. Protects API responses even for public endpoints.

Filter 5: CsrfFilter
    /*
     CSRF = Cross-Site Request Forgery
     ATTACK: Evil website tricks logged-in user's browser into
             making requests to YOUR app using their session cookie.
     FIX: Every state-changing request must include a secret CSRF token
          that only YOUR frontend knows.
    */
    // How CSRF attack works (WITHOUT protection):
    // 1. User logs into bank.com → session cookie stored in browser
    // 2. User visits evil.com
    // 3. evil.com has hidden form: POST bank.com/transfer?to=hacker&amount=10000
    // 4. Browser auto-sends session cookie → bank processes it! 😱
    // CSRF Token fix:
    // Server sends hidden token → client must echo it back in every POST/PUT/DELETE
    // ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
    // │  FOR JWT APIs → DISABLE CSRF                │
    // │                                             │
    // │  JWT is sent in Authorization header        │
    // │  NOT in cookies → CSRF attack impossible!   │
    // │  Browsers don't auto-send headers ✅        │
    // └─────────────────────────────────────────────┘
    http.csrf(csrf -> csrf.disable());   // ← correct for JWT REST APIs
    // FOR OAuth2 with sessions → KEEP CSRF ENABLED (default)

Filter 6: LogoutFilter
    /*
     Intercepts requests to the logout URL (default: POST /logout)
     Performs logout actions:
      - Invalidates session
      - Clears SecurityContext
      - Clears remember-me cookies
      - Redirects to login page
    */
    // Default behavior:
    POST /logout → session invalidated → redirect to /login?logout
    // Custom logout config:
    http.logout(logout -> logout
        .logoutUrl("/auth/logout")                    // custom logout URL
        .logoutSuccessUrl("/login?logged-out=true")   // redirect after logout
        .deleteCookies("JSESSIONID", "remember-me")   // clear cookies
        .invalidateHttpSession(true)                  // destroy session
        .clearAuthentication(true)                    // clear SecurityContext
    );
    // FOR JWT:
    // Logout is handled CLIENT-SIDE (just delete the token from storage)
    // Server-side: optionally maintain a token blacklist in Redis
    @PostMapping("/auth/logout")
    public ResponseEntity<String> logout(
            @RequestHeader("Authorization") String token) {
        // Add token to Redis blacklist until expiry
        tokenBlacklist.add(token.substring(7));
        return ResponseEntity.ok("Logged out");
    }

Filter 7: UsernamePasswordAuthenticationFilter
    /*
     Handles traditional form-based login:
     POST /login with username & password in request body/form
     Flow:
     1. Intercepts POST /login
     2. Extracts username + password
     3. Creates UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken
     4. Passes to AuthenticationManager
     5. AuthenticationManager calls UserDetailsService.loadUserByUsername()
     6. Compares password with BCrypt
     7. Success → sets SecurityContext
     8. Failure → throws BadCredentialsException
    */
    // FOR JWT:
    // We DON'T use this filter for login
    // Instead we have our OWN /auth/login endpoint in a controller
    // This filter is replaced by JwtAuthFilter for subsequent requests
    // FOR OAuth2:
    // This filter is bypassed — OAuth2LoginAuthenticationFilter handles it instead
    // Customize if needed:
    public class CustomAuthFilter extends UsernamePasswordAuthenticationFilter {
        @Override
        public Authentication attemptAuthentication(
                HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response) {
            // Read JSON body instead of form params
            LoginRequest loginReq = objectMapper.readValue(request.getInputStream(),
                                                            LoginRequest.class);
            return authManager.authenticate(
                new UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken(
                    loginReq.getEmail(), loginReq.getPassword()
                )
            );
        }
    }

Filter 8: BearerTokenAuthenticationFilter (OAuth2 Resource Server)
    /*
     Specifically for OAuth2 Resource Server setup.
     Extracts Bearer token from Authorization header and validates it.
     Flow:
     1. Read "Authorization: Bearer <token>" header
     2. Pass token to OAuth2TokenIntrospectionClient OR JwtDecoder
     3. Validate token (signature, expiry, issuer, audience)
     4. Extract claims → build Authentication object
     5. Set in SecurityContext
    */
    // Config to activate this filter:
    http.oauth2ResourceServer(oauth2 -> oauth2
        .jwt(jwt -> jwt
            .decoder(JwtDecoders.fromIssuerLocation("https://accounts.google.com"))
        )
    );
    // application.yml for Resource Server:
    spring:
      security:
        oauth2:
          resourceserver:
            jwt:
              issuer-uri: https://accounts.google.com
              # Spring auto-fetches public keys from Google's JWKS endpoint

Filter 9: OAuth2LoginAuthenticationFilter
    /*
     Handles the CALLBACK after user logs in at Google/GitHub.
     OAuth2 Flow Step:
     1. User clicks "Login with Google"
     2. Redirected to Google login
     3. Google redirects back to: /login/oauth2/code/google?code=ABC
     4. THIS FILTER intercepts that callback URL
     5. Exchanges authorization code for access token
     6. Fetches user info from Google
     7. Creates/updates user in your DB
     8. Sets SecurityContext
    */
    // Default callback URL pattern:
    /login/oauth2/code/{registrationId}
    // e.g. /login/oauth2/code/google
    //      /login/oauth2/code/github
    // Customize user loading:
    @Service
    public class CustomOAuth2UserService extends DefaultOAuth2UserService {
        @Autowired
        private UserRepository userRepo;
        @Override
        public OAuth2User loadUser(OAuth2UserRequest userRequest) throws OAuth2AuthenticationException {
            OAuth2User oAuth2User = super.loadUser(userRequest);
            String email = oAuth2User.getAttribute("email");
            String name  = oAuth2User.getAttribute("name");
            // Auto-register user on first OAuth2 login
            userRepo.findByEmail(email).orElseGet(() -> {
                User newUser = new User(name, email, "ROLE_USER");
                return userRepo.save(newUser);
            });
    
            return oAuth2User;
        }
    }
Filter 10: ExceptionTranslationFilter
    /*
     Catches TWO specific security exceptions and converts them to HTTP responses:
     1. AuthenticationException → 401 Unauthorized
        (user is not logged in / token missing / token invalid)
    
     2. AccessDeniedException   → 403 Forbidden
        (user IS logged in but doesn't have required role)
    */
    // Customize 401 response:
    http.exceptionHandling(ex -> ex
        .authenticationEntryPoint((request, response, authException) -> {
            response.setContentType("application/json");
            response.setStatus(401);
            response.getWriter().write("""
                {
                  "status": 401,
                  "error": "Unauthorized",
                  "message": "Token missing or invalid"
                }
            """);
        })
        // Customize 403 response:
        .accessDeniedHandler((request, response, accessDeniedException) -> {
            response.setContentType("application/json");
            response.setStatus(403);
            response.getWriter().write("""
                {
                  "status": 403,
                  "error": "Forbidden",
                  "message": "You don't have permission to access this resource"
                }
            """);
        })
    );

Filter 11: AuthorizationFilter (formerly FilterSecurityInterceptor)
    /*
     THE FINAL GATEKEEPER — runs last.
     Checks if the authenticated user has permission to access the URL.
     This is WHERE your authorizeHttpRequests() rules are enforced.
    */
    
    // This filter reads your rules:
    .authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth
        .requestMatchers("/auth/**").permitAll()
        .requestMatchers("/api/admin/**").hasRole("ADMIN")
        .anyRequest().authenticated()
    )
    
    // And makes the final Allow/Deny decision:
    // ✅ User has ADMIN role + hits /api/admin → ALLOW
    // ❌ User has USER role  + hits /api/admin → AccessDeniedException → 403
    // ❌ No token            + hits /api/user  → AuthenticationException → 401

Filter                                Purpose                      JWT              OAuth2
DisableEncodeUrlFilter                No session ID in URLs        ✅ Active      ✅ Active
WebAsyncManagerIntegrationFilter      Async thread security        ✅ Active      ✅ Active
SecurityContextHolderFilter           Load/clear security context  ✅ Active      ✅ Active
HeaderWriterFilter                    Add security headers         ✅ Active      ✅ Active
CsrfFilter                            CSRF protection              ❌ Disabled    ✅ Active
LogoutFilter                          Handle logout                ✅ Active      ✅ Active
JwtAuthFilter                         Validate JWT token           ✅ Custom     ➖ Optional
OAuth2LoginAuthenticationFilter       Handle OAuth2 callback      ❌ Not used      ✅ Active
BearerTokenAuthenticationFilter        Validate OAuth2 token      ❌ Not used      ✅ Resource server
ExceptionTranslationFilter            401 / 403 responses          ✅ Active        ✅ Active
AuthorizationFilter                    Enforce URL rules          ✅ Active        ✅ Active

http.authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth
    // ── Public Access ──────────────────────────────────────
    .requestMatchers("/", "/login", "/register").permitAll()
    // Anyone can access — no token needed
    // Use for: login page, signup, public homepage, health check
    .requestMatchers("/api/public/**").permitAll()
    // /** means all sub-paths: /api/public/news, /api/public/prices etc.
    // ── Role Based ─────────────────────────────────────────
    .requestMatchers("/api/admin/**").hasRole("ADMIN")
    // Only ROLE_ADMIN — Spring auto-prepends "ROLE_"
    // hasRole("ADMIN") checks for "ROLE_ADMIN" in authorities
    .requestMatchers("/api/manager/**").hasAnyRole("ADMIN", "MANAGER")
    // Either role works
    .requestMatchers("/api/user/**").hasAuthority("USER_READ")
    // Exact authority string — no "ROLE_" prefix added
    // Use for fine-grained permissions
    // ── HTTP Method + Path Combo ───────────────────────────
    .requestMatchers(HttpMethod.GET, "/api/products/**").permitAll()
    // Anyone can READ products
    .requestMatchers(HttpMethod.POST, "/api/products/**").hasRole("ADMIN")
    // Only ADMIN can CREATE products
    .requestMatchers(HttpMethod.DELETE, "/api/products/**").hasRole("ADMIN")
    // Only ADMIN can DELETE products
    // ── IP Address Restriction ─────────────────────────────
    .requestMatchers("/actuator/**").access(
        new WebExpressionAuthorizationManager("hasRole('ADMIN') and hasIpAddress('192.168.1.0/24')")
    )
    // Admin role AND must come from internal network
    // ── Authenticated vs Anonymous ─────────────────────────
    .anyRequest().authenticated()
    // All other requests need a valid token/session — any role
    // .anyRequest().permitAll()      ← everything public (not recommended)
    // .anyRequest().denyAll()        ← everything blocked (whitelist approach)
);

 How Rules Are Evaluated:
1. The Golden Rules of Authorization
    RULE 1: TOP → BOTTOM evaluation, FIRST MATCH WINS
    RULE 2: Most SPECIFIC rules first, GENERIC rules last
    RULE 3: anyRequest() MUST always be LAST
    RULE 4: Order WRONG = security holes or everything blocked

2. What Happens Without Correct Order
    // ❌ WRONG ORDER — Security Hole!
    .authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth
        .anyRequest().authenticated()           // catches EVERYTHING first
        .requestMatchers("/auth/**").permitAll() // NEVER REACHED
        .requestMatchers("/api/admin/**").hasRole("ADMIN") // NEVER REACHED
    )
    // Result: /auth/login also needs authentication → infinite loop!

      // ❌ WRONG ORDER — Too Permissive!
      .authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth
          .requestMatchers("/api/**").permitAll()  // /api/admin also becomes public!
          .requestMatchers("/api/admin/**").hasRole("ADMIN") // NEVER REACHED
          .anyRequest().authenticated()
      )
      // Result: /api/admin/deleteAll is now PUBLIC! 😱

      // ✅ CORRECT ORDER — Specific → Generic
      .authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth
          .requestMatchers("/auth/**").permitAll()          // most specific public
          .requestMatchers("/api/admin/**").hasRole("ADMIN") // specific + restricted
          .requestMatchers("/api/user/**").hasRole("USER")   // specific + restricted
          .requestMatchers("/api/**").authenticated()        // broad API rule
          .anyRequest().authenticated()                      // catch-all LAST
      )

3. Rule Evaluation Flow — Step by Step
Incoming Request: DELETE /api/admin/users/5
User roles: [ROLE_USER]

┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│               AuthorizationFilter evaluates rules           │
│                                                             │
│  Rule 1: /auth/**              → ❌ no match → next        │
│  Rule 2: /public/**            → ❌ no match → next        │
│  Rule 3: /api/admin/**         → ✅ MATCH!                 │
│           hasRole("ADMIN")     → user has ROLE_USER only   │
│                                → 🚫 ACCESS DENIED → 403   │
│  Rule 4,5... never evaluated                                │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

Incoming Request: GET /health
User: NOT authenticated

┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Rule 1: /auth/**   → ❌ no match                          │
│  Rule 2: /public/** → ❌ no match                          │
│  Rule 3: /api/**    → ❌ no match                          │
│  Rule 4: anyRequest → ✅ MATCH! → authenticated()         │
│           user NOT logged in → 401 Unauthorized            │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
Role vs Permission Based — The Difference

ROLE BASED (coarse-grained):          PERMISSION BASED (fine-grained):
─────────────────────────────         ────────────────────────────────
ROLE_ADMIN  → can do everything       users:read
ROLE_USER   → limited access          users:write
ROLE_GUEST  → read only               orders:read
                                      orders:delete
                                      reports:view

// Role-based (simple apps):
.hasRole("ADMIN")
// Permission-based (enterprise apps):
.hasAuthority("orders:delete")
// COMBINED (best practice):
@PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN') or hasAuthority('orders:delete')")
public void deleteOrder(Long id) { }

Method Level Security — @PreAuthorize
  Used when URL rules aren't enough — secure at the method level:
    @Configuration
    @EnableMethodSecurity   // ← must enable this!
    public class SecurityConfig { }
    @RestController
    @RequestMapping("/api/users")
    public class UserController {
        // ── Role checks ───────────────────────────────────────────
        @GetMapping
        @PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')")
        public List<User> getAllUsers() { }
        // Only ADMIN can list all users
        @DeleteMapping("/{id}")
        @PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')")
        public void deleteUser(@PathVariable Long id) { }
        // ── Permission checks ─────────────────────────────────────
        @GetMapping("/reports")
        @PreAuthorize("hasAuthority('reports:view')")
        public List<Report> getReports() { }
        // ── Dynamic checks using method args ─────────────────────
        @GetMapping("/{id}")
        @PreAuthorize("#id == authentication.principal.id or hasRole('ADMIN')")
        public User getUser(@PathVariable Long id) { }
        // Users can only fetch THEIR OWN profile
        // Admins can fetch anyone's profile
        // #id refers to the method parameter 'id'
        @PutMapping("/{id}")
        @PreAuthorize("#request.ownerId == authentication.principal.id")
        public User updateUser(@PathVariable Long id,
                               @RequestBody UpdateRequest request) { }
        // ── Post-check on returned data ───────────────────────────
        @GetMapping("/{id}/data")
        @PostAuthorize("returnObject.email == authentication.name")
        public User getUserData(@PathVariable Long id) {
            return userService.findById(id);
            // Even if query runs, returned object is checked
            // If email doesn't match logged-in user → 403
        }
        // ── Combined conditions ───────────────────────────────────
        @PostMapping("/promote/{id}")
        @PreAuthorize("hasRole('SUPER_ADMIN') and #id != authentication.principal.id")
        public void promoteToAdmin(@PathVariable Long id) { }
        // Only SUPER_ADMIN can promote
        // Cannot promote yourself
        // ── Custom bean method in SpEL ────────────────────────────
        @GetMapping("/{id}/orders")
        @PreAuthorize("@userSecurity.isOwnerOrAdmin(authentication, #id)")
        public List<Order> getUserOrders(@PathVariable Long id) { }
    }
    
    // Custom security bean:
    @Component("userSecurity")
    public class UserSecurityService {
        public boolean isOwnerOrAdmin(Authentication auth, Long userId) {
            UserDetails user = (UserDetails) auth.getPrincipal();
            boolean isAdmin = user.getAuthorities().stream()
                .anyMatch(a -> a.getAuthority().equals("ROLE_ADMIN"));
            boolean isOwner = user.getUsername().equals(
                userRepository.findById(userId).get().getEmail()
            );
            return isAdmin || isOwner;
        }
    }

URL Rules vs Method Rules — When to Use What
┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│         authorizeHttpRequests (URL level)                  │
│                                                            │
│  ✅ Use for:                                               │
│    Broad path-based rules (/api/admin/**)                  │
│    HTTP method restrictions (GET public, POST admin)       │
│    Public endpoints (permitAll)                            │
│    First line of defense                                   │
│                                                            │
│  ❌ Cannot do:                                             │
│    Check method parameters                                 │
│    Check returned object values                            │
│    Complex business logic conditions                       │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                          
┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│         @PreAuthorize (Method level)                       │
│                                                            │
│  ✅ Use for:                                               │
│    Fine-grained control on specific methods                │
│    Checking method arguments (#id == principal.id)         │
│    Complex SpEL expressions                                │
│    Custom bean logic (@myBean.check())                     │
│    Ownership checks (can user access THIS resource?)       │
│                                                            │
│  ❌ Overkill for:                                          │
│    Simple broad rules (use URL rules instead)              │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

Best Practice: USE BOTH TOGETHER
URL rules = broad gatekeeper
Method rules = fine-grained controller

Role Hierarchy — Avoid Repeating Roles Everywhere
    // WITHOUT hierarchy — tedious:
    .hasAnyRole("ADMIN", "MANAGER", "USER")  // repeated everywhere
    .hasAnyRole("ADMIN", "MANAGER")
    .hasAnyRole("ADMIN")
    
    // WITH hierarchy — clean:
    @Bean
    public RoleHierarchy roleHierarchy() {
        RoleHierarchyImpl h = new RoleHierarchyImpl();
        h.setHierarchy("""
            ROLE_SUPER_ADMIN > ROLE_ADMIN
            ROLE_ADMIN       > ROLE_MANAGER
            ROLE_MANAGER     > ROLE_USER
            ROLE_USER        > ROLE_GUEST
        """);
        return h;
    }
    // Now just write:
    .hasRole("USER")
    // ROLE_USER, ROLE_MANAGER, ROLE_ADMIN, ROLE_SUPER_ADMIN all pass ✅
    // Visual:
    ROLE_SUPER_ADMIN
        └── ROLE_ADMIN
                └── ROLE_MANAGER
                        └── ROLE_USER
                                └── ROLE_GUEST

Method           Checks            Auto ROLE_ prefix  Example
permitAll()      Nothing                 —              Public endpoints
denyAll()        Nothing                 —              Block all
authenticated()  Has valid token         —              Any logged-in user
hasRole()        Single role            ✅Yes           hasRole("ADMIN")
hasAnyRole()      Multiple roles        ✅ Yes          hasAnyRole("USER","ADMIN")
hasAuthority()   Single permission      ❌ No            hasAuthority("READ")
hasAnyAuthority() Multiple permissions  ❌ No            hasAnyAuthority("READ","WRITE")
@PreAuthorize      SpEL expression        ✅ Yes            #id == principal.id
@PostAuthorize    Return object            ✅ Yes          returnObject.owner == principal

Complete Flow Summary:
Request Arrives
      │
      ▼
JwtAuthFilter
  ├── Valid JWT → set SecurityContext (user + roles)
  └── No JWT   → pass through (anonymous)
      │
      ▼
AuthorizationFilter reads rules TOP → BOTTOM
  ├── First matching rule WINS
  ├── permitAll()     → allow everyone
  ├── hasRole(X)      → check ROLE_X in SecurityContext
  ├── authenticated() → check if SecurityContext has user
  └── denyAll()       → block everyone
      │
      ├── ✅ ALLOWED → reaches Controller
      │        │
      │        ▼
      │   @PreAuthorize  (second layer check)
      │        │
      │        ├── ✅ passes → method executes
      │        └── ❌ fails  → 403 Forbidden
      │
      └── ❌ DENIED
               ├── Not authenticated → 401 Unauthorized
               └── Wrong role        → 403 Forbidden
